ðŸ›  Step 1: Create Hosted Zone in Route 53

Go to Route 53 â†’ Hosted zones â†’ Create hosted zone

Domain name: zaltix.com

Type: Public hosted zone

Click Create.

AWS will give you Name Server (NS) records â†’ update these NS values in your domain registrar (e.g., GoDaddy, Namecheap).

ðŸ›  Step 2: Add DNS Records

Inside hosted zone, click Create record:

For login.zaltix.com â†’ point to ALB DNS name

Record type: A (alias)

Value: Your ALB DNS (e.g., alb-123456.elb.amazonaws.com)

TTL: 60 seconds.

For any CNAME you need (optional):

Example: api.zaltix.com â†’ backend-alb-xxxx.elb.amazonaws.com

Verify with commands in your terminal:

ping login.zaltix.com
nslookup login.zaltix.com


You should see it resolving to the ALB.

ðŸ›  Step 3: Request SSL Certificate in ACM

Go to AWS Certificate Manager (ACM) â†’ Request a certificate.

Choose Request a public certificate.

Add domains:

zaltix.com

*.zaltix.com (for all subdomains like login.zaltix.com).

Choose DNS validation.

ACM will show a CNAME record for validation â†’ Click Create records in Route 53.
(This automatically creates validation record in hosted zone).

Wait until the status shows Issued.

ðŸ›  Step 4: Configure HTTPS on Load Balancer

Go to EC2 â†’ Load balancers.

Select your Application Load Balancer (ALB).

Add Listener for HTTPS (443):

Protocol: HTTPS

Port: 443

Default action: Forward to your target group.

SSL Certificate: Select the ACM certificate you created.

Also edit existing HTTP (80) listener:

Action â†’ Redirect to HTTPS (443).

Save changes.

ðŸ›  Step 5: Test Access

Open browser â†’ https://login.zaltix.com
It should load via HTTPS with a green lock âœ….

Try accessing http://login.zaltix.com â†’ should automatically redirect to HTTPS.

âœ… Now your flow is:

Route53 â†’ DNS resolution (login.zaltix.com â†’ ALB)

ACM â†’ SSL cert validation

ALB â†’ Handles HTTPS (443) with cert

